The 'bees car' that avoids collision
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating the bees’ flight, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Centre have created this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research from the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the Director-General of Public Relations for Technology and Marketing Research and Development, the BR23C represents the Nissan Security Shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collision.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that looks a lot like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important is the eyes composed of the bee, capable of seeing in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers developed what is called a Laser Range Finder (Laser Range Finder).
This detects the obstacles that are at a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor immediately to avoid the obstacle.
“At the time he detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurking its 90-degree or more wheels to avoid collision.
The biggest difference to any other existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that was the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Movement Laboratory and senior engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down or in diagonal; it can move only in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like the bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotational function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
“Each second this device must only process information and act according to those data.
It doesn’t need to keep the information or the intuitive logic of prior maneuvers, that’s why it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB memory.
This may surprise, but we do not talk about gigabytes of memory, nor even megabytes.”
This represents the first cause of developing new collision instant prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced in serial cars within a decade after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last more than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a satellite navigation GPS system to guide the driver to its destination by avoiding road barriers.
