Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refounded the republic around socialism of the 21st century.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, it was the third one who put a draft new Constitution to the voice.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted “yes” at the referendum, according to official results of 80% of votes.
According to these results, the "no" achieved 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two surveys carried out at the exit of the voting offices and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a wide “yes” victory, between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution in the night of Sunday to Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he assured, congratulating the Equatorians at the headquarters of Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales as well as his Chilian counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place in calm according to the Observation Mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a 444-point text consolidating the President’s defended “new socialism”.
The draft Constitution devotes the State’s power on the economy, reserved the “planning of development” of a country living essentially from oil extraction by foreign companies and the currency that its immigrants send.
The draft, elected by Correa in 2006, also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who will be able to perform up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and strike a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began establishing in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives under the threshold of poverty.
It finally provides for the ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuador base as the starting point of U.S. drug operations.
The 19 hostages have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault against the kidnappers of eleven tourists and their eight accompaniers captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back on Monday afternoon to the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at around 15:30 a.m. on board a special aircraft at the al-Maza military base, joined at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to talk to the press, on board helicopters to the Maadi hospital, a residential outskirts of Cairo, to undergo examinations.
They're in "good health," and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 in a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, at the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been voted from one hidden to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanians - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard and the director of the safari organizator Aegyptus.
An Egyptian safety official said 30 special forces, on board two helicopters, had launched the attack in the night just before dawn.
"A fire exchange happened, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," said the official who requested anonymity.
He said that 150 Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commando.
Head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result through professionalism and the effectiveness of our men of secret services, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the previous day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board, killing six, including the Chadian chief, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement had immediately denied.
