A ridge in the chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their purchases of drugs.
Experts in information protection are afraid that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that binds the use of information concerning the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the agreement of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is to entrust his chicken to a pig," said Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage medication prescriptions, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies are dependent on the insurance premium and insured capital in the event of damage, the health status of the customer who presents themselves, and if they believe that the risk is too large, they do not even guarantee it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after took awareness of the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is easily provided with pharmacies, data about the purchase of drugs of the person within the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself what illness the person is suffering from, and what is his health status.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducing, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it into a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is nothing left to do with the insurer except the paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat bubbles, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data, and they must ask for authorization from the patient before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are constrained by the authorities, even though they have not been sanctioned for their faults in the past.
Some companies have recently also processed the results of laboratory analyses, and link them to the data on drug consumption, in this way they are able to provide even more accurate portrait of patients’ health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and the control of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate medical data protection law, but its scope of action extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on the expansion of the control circle of authorities concerning companies specialized in data supply is currently in front of the Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not sufficient and that is why he has developed his program further, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
This is another question of whether the data subject is truly free to agree or not, since if he refuses, the insurances do not sign a contract with him.
Thus and ultimately, the chickens depend on the kindness of the cow.
